   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Outliers"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b4ed9df5-67b6-4ed3-9ae4-505132934608",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "To verify whether the outliers identified in the boxplots are valid values or measurement errors, we plot Rotational Speed vs Torque. This allows us to see if the outliers behave differently from the rest of the data."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "id": "d01792ad-976e-4215-af7f-ae2e200485f1",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 800x500 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.scatter(\n",
    "    df1[df1['Machine failure'] == 0]['Rotational speed [rpm]'],\n",
    "    df1[df1['Machine failure'] == 0]['Torque [Nm]'],\n",
    "    alpha=0.3,\n",
    "    label = 'No failure'\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.scatter(\n",
    "    df1[df1['Machine failure'] == 1]['Rotational speed [rpm]'],\n",
    "    df1[df1['Machine failure'] == 1]['Torque [Nm]'],\n",
    "    alpha=0.8,\n",
    "    label = 'Failure'\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.xlabel('RPM')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Torque')\n",
    "plt.title('RPM vs Torque by Failure')\n",
    "plt.legend()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f888a339-fee9-4677-910c-584d4ca21db6",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This shows that the outliers identified in the boxplots follow the same pattern as the rest of the data. They do not cluster separately nor show unusual behavior when compared against failure and non-failure. Based on this, we conclude that these are valid values not measurement errors and will be kept for model training."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0c51eab3-156c-496d-8174-0b03f6e3042a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Feature Engineering\n",
    "\n",
    "First, we drop columns that would cause data leakage. The failure type columns (TWF, HDF, PWF, OSF, RNF) are sub-categories of the target variable Machine Failure, if any of them equals 1, machine failure is also 1. Including them would allow the model to \"see\" the answer during training, making the evaluation results unreliable.  \n",
    "Then we encode the categorical variable 'Type' using one-hot encoding with drop_first=True to avoid multicollinearity. Finally, we create three new features based on the data knowledge."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "id": "02292545-11bb-47d6-87d7-94865ae1075a",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "df1.drop(columns= ['TWF', 'HDF', 'PWF', 'OSF', 'RNF'], axis= 1, inplace= True, errors = 'ignore')"
   ]
  },
